[4] Cholera - Zambia
Date: Tue 2 Nov 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhuanet [edited]
<http://www.chinaview.cn>

Fresh cholera outbreak in Zambia
---------------------------------
A new wave of Cholera broke out in Lusaka, the capital of Zambia, 8 months
after health authorities said a previous outbreak had been contained. The
latest outbreak was reported in the densely populated Chaisa area, in the
northern outskirts of the city.
Victor Mukonka, spokesperson for the Central Board of Health, gave
confirmation in an interview on Tue 2 Nov 2004, saying that an infected
woman was treated and discharged from a local clinic. He warned the disease
could spread quickly unless Lusaka residents took necessary precautions,
including observing high standards of hygiene.
The Health Ministry said that by February 2004, Zambia had reported some
3835 cholera cases, including 179 deaths.
Health NGO Medecins Sans Frontieres-Spain (Doctors without Borders) and the
WHO helped to bring that epidemic under control. However, last month
[October 2004], the Central Statistical Office warned of a high diarrhea
prevalence of 21 percent among children under the age of 5.
